<subSubSection pageId="142" pageNumber="743" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="142.[703,1295,2786,3205]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[703,858,2786,2811]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heller" authorityYear="1912" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="orestes" subSpecies="dollmani">Otomys orestes dollmani Heller, 1912</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation pageId="142" pageNumber="743">Mount Gargues (Urguess), 7000 ft (= 2130 m), Matthews Range, Kenya.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="142" pageNumber="743" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="142.[703,1295,2786,3205]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heller" authorityYear="1912" box="[707,928,2895,2929]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dollmani">Otomys dollmani</taxonomicName>
previously was included under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1900" box="[805,924,2943,2968]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orestes">O. orestes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brants" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[945,1096,2943,2968]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="irroratus">O. irroratus</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1902" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tropicalis">O. tropicalis</taxonomicName>
but was shown to be morphologically distinct (small size and dark color, with relatively long tail and six laminae on M?). Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="142" pageNumber="743" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" startId="142.[704,876,3132,3166]" targetBox="[90,680,2790,3202]" targetPageId="142">
<paragraph blockId="142.[703,1295,2786,3205]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[704,880,3132,3166]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from Mt Gargues, Mathews Range, C Kenya.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="142" pageNumber="743" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="142.[91,1294,3219,3482]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[91,340,3219,3244]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 138-150 mm, tail 85-105 mm, hindfoot 23-27 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Dollman’s Vlei Ratis relatively large and robust, with large blunt head, short tail, and shaggy fur. Dorsum is dark brown. Tail 1s relatively long for 
<taxonomicName box="[347,437,3329,3363]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Otomys</taxonomicName>
(c.63% of head-body length). Upper and lowerincisors each have deep and shallow grooves. M, has four laminae, and M?® hassix laminae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[92,835,3409,3443]" pageId="142" pageNumber="743" type="biology_ecology">
